  "business_context": "Email records hold the substance of email communication tracked in the CRM. Two main use cases: (1) sales/service email logging — a rep sends or receives a one-to-one email with a customer; the email gets logged on the relevant Account / Contact / Opportunity / Case so the next person looking at the record can see what was said. (2) marketing email tracking — a bulk email goes out as part of a campaign; per- recipient send/open/click events get tracked but typically not stored as individual Email records (instead via Campaign Member status). Email entities are surprisingly divergent across systems. Salesforce has EmailMessage with rich tracking, plus the legacy Task-with- TaskSubtype=Email pattern. HubSpot models email as an Engagement subtype. Attio has Emails as a first-class entity, auto-synced from Gmail/Outlook. EspoCRM has Email as a separate entity with full inbox / sent folder structure (Email Account configuration drives sync). CiviCRM uses Activity-of-type-Email. Bloomerang has Interaction-of- type-Email (less rich tracking). When interviewing clients, surface \"Email\" by asking whether email correspondence with customers/donors should appear on the relevant CRM record's timeline (yes for almost every deployment) and whether they need bulk/marketing email capabilities (varies). Email-tracking depth (just-logged vs full open/click tracking) is a major capability differentiator across systems.",
